description:
Superman has stumbled upon a hidden laboratory he's been looking for weeks. He is startled to see that numerous data about him has been collected about him there. Superman flies up with the laboratory and places it at a Lagrange Point in space. Coming back to Metropolis, he finds an attempted bank heist and a new villain. They start fighting each other and it is later revealed that the villain is Metallo, a man with a heart of Kryptonite and with enough power to kill Superman. But during the fight, someone abducts Metallo, probably to serve his own ends...

Notes:

  • First post-Crisis appearance of Kryptonite.
  • First post-Crisis appearance of Metallo.
  • "History on the Drawing Board" one page text piece by John Byrne.

description:
The story opens with images of Lana Lang flashing on all of Lexcorp’s computer screens. The supervisors tell Luthor that the woman has been seen almost every time that Superman has appeared to save the city. Lex Luthor thinks that she might be a lover or a relative of Superman, and keeps a picture of her with him for future reference. Luthor then politely orders Amanda McCoy, her computer scientist, to be his partner for that night’s dinner.

Luthor then goes to another chamber, where he has kept the captured Metallo. Dr. Happersen explains that they cannot extract the Kryptonite chunk from his innards because it is his source of power. Metallo defies the neuro-neutralizers to be able to talk. He tells Luthor that he is making a mistake by capturing Metallo, because though rich and influential, he does not have the power to defeat Superman. Luthor doesn’t proceed with the argument and rips off the kryptonite from Metallo’s body. He then hands it over to Happersen for analysis.

Meanwhile, back in Smallville, two of Luthor’s men go over to the farmhouse and knock out Joseph and Martha with a tranquilizer gun. They ransack the house, find a scrapbook full of Superman clippings and take it. They knock into Lana Lang on their way out. Concerned about endangering their mission, they shoot her too and take her along with the Kents.

Elsewhere, Luthor is having dinner with Amanda. Amanda is displeased, but is way too much afraid to disclose her feelings. Luthor receives a call from his tower and goes away. Back in the tower, he sees the captured Lana Lang and immediately recognizes her from the pictures taken earlier. The doctor comes and explains that any attempt to make her speak the truth with drugs could prove fatal for her, because she is allergic to drugs.

The next day, Superman is flying over Metropolis, when he spots an aerial camera following him. He tries various ways to out fly the camera but fails, understanding that it is built with advanced technology. He borrows some balloons and throws them in front of the device, thus confusing it momentarily. He grabs it from behind, but it explodes with a blinding flash. Superman comes back to his apartment as Clark Kent, and is shocked to find Lana Lang inside. Lana is bruised and bleeding, emaciated and in rags. Lana begs of him to help hide her from Luthor. She then tells him how she endured Luthor’s cruel tortures and yet kept Superman’s identity a secret. Clark is thankful and tends to her.

Luthor tells Amanda that he let Lana Lang escape because she would find her way to Clark ’s apartment. Clark would definitely tell his friend Superman to look into the matter. So Luthor has set a trap for Superman inside a factory complex.

Superman bursts into the factory, but it explodes. Minutes later, he comes to Luthor, blaming him for the events. Luthor is wearing a ring with a piece of Kryptonite in it. It makes Superman stagger. Luthor tells him how he hates him and asks him to go away. Superman flies back with Lana, and is surprised to find Ma and Pa Kent home. They inform him of the recent events.

Luthor’s computers come up with a solution, “Clark is Superman”. Luthor is disappointed with the results and doesn’t believe them. He fires Amanda and says that he has other plans for Superman.

Notes:

  • First appearance of Lex Luthor's Kryptonite Ring.
  • "Special thanks to Keith Williams for background inks."
  • "Meanwhile" one page text piece by Dick Giordano featuring "Superman's Other Creators".

description:
While Lois interviews Glorious Godfrey, Superman is transported to Apokolips by Darkseid and is shocked by the conditions there.

Full Plot

Lois Lane comes to the Grande Hotel to interview Mr. G. Gordon Godfrey for his campaign against super-heroes. Godfrey’s personal guard is almost thinking Lois is a threat to his master. Godfrey apologizes to Lois, but does not differ from his point when asked about super-heroes. He tells that super-heroes are a menace. The world would have been a better place without them. Personally, he would wipe out all of them if he could.

Elsewhere, Clark is running wildly through the streets. But not without reason. A pair of Omega Beams are following his every move. Clark ducks into the sewers, but does not escape the beams. They hit him and he disappears.

As to where he appears next, Clark is bewildered to see himself standing before Darkseid. Darkseid is disappointed. He had sent forth his Omega Beams to seek out Superman, not Clark. The Phantom Stranger, who too is standing there, prefers to remain silent. He knows who Clark is. Darkseid is furious and hurls Clark out of the window. Kent falls below into the streets of Armagetto. He is immediately attacked by the hunger dogs, who almost strip him of his clothes. Clark changes into Superman and frightens them away. Then he spots Parademons flying overhead. Fearing he might reveal his dual identity, Superman covers himself in rags and ventures outside to mix with the people.

Superman spots people shouting. He sees that some royal guards have taken a woman prisoner for preaching against Darkseid and are about to execute her. Superman breaks into the restricted area and helps the woman to escape. Then he confronts the guards. The guards deploy a Pacifier to deal with Superman. Superman puts up a fight with the pacifier. After a brief struggle, he tears up the armor to reveal a glommer. The glommer jumps at its first chance to take over Superman’s central nervous system. It compels Superman to fly into one of the huge Fire-Pits.

Darkseid watches the whole incident from his tower and lets out a bellowing laugh.

Notes:

  • Legends crossover Chapter 17.
  • Most New God characters have cameo appearances.
  • The first post-Crisis meeting between Superman and Darkseid.
  • A letter to the editor from T M Maple.
  • The story continues in Adventures of Superman #426.
name: Legends from the Darkside

description:
Bloodsport... He plays for keeps!

"Bloodsport!" Imagine the death and destruction a sadistic madman could cause if he were able to have any weapon he could think of appear in his hand simply by wishing it to. Well the man called Bloodsport has this ability. Can Superman stop this maniacal killer before more innocent lives are lost? Featuring Jimmy Olsen.

Notes:

  • This story takes place on December 23rd.
  • First appearance of Maggie Sawyer.
  • Kryptonite needles used by Bloodsport injured Superman.
  • "Dedicated to the names on the Black Wall - - and those who remember them."

description:
"The Mummy Strikes!" Part 1 of 2. Featuring a special guest-appearance by Wonder Woman. In the aftermath of the ordeal with G. Gordon Godfrey and Darkseid (see Legends #1-6), Clark just can't seem to get the Amazing Amazon off his mind. Meanwhile, star reporter Lois Lane is on hand at an archeological dig for the find of the century. But when communications are suddenly cut off, the Man of Steel springs into action.

Notes:

  • Wonder Woman appears in a dream sequence.
  • The package Clark has on his desk contains the Superman Scrapbook.
  • First appearances of Allie and Whit.
name: The Mummy Strikes

description:
"The Last Five-Hundred!" Part 2 of 2. Superman is one of the mightiest heroes in the universe, but can even his great powers compare to the abilities of the Last 500? And, can the Man of Steel somehow find a way to defeat this new foe without hurting his friends, whose minds have been usurped by his enemy?

Notes:

  • A letter to the editor from T. M. Maple.
name: The Last Five Hundred

description:
Superman meets the awesome might of the hulking "Rampage". Kitty Faulkner was a scientist appointed by the Daily Planet to be at an experimental environmental machine. However things went wrong and Kitty would be part of an accidental explosion. Transformed into a massive, solar-powered, super-strong, orange skinned behemoth, Rampage was born. It took all of the Man of Steel's might to fight her off and revert her to Kitty.

Notes:

  • First post-Crisis appearance of Dan Turpin.
  • First appearance of Kitty Faulkner and Rampage.
name: Rampage!

description:
Part 2 of 4. After an unexpected attack by Superboy in the past, the Legion of Super-Heroes escaped in the Time Bubble several years into the future and landed in Superman's time period. The Legion and Superman met for the first time which confused members of the Legion except for Brainiac 5. Superboy was able to follow the Legion and captured them as well.

Notes:

  • "Dedicated to the memory of Edmond Hamilton."
  • "Meanwhile..." one page text piece by Dick Giordano dedicated to the recent passing of E. Nelson Bridwell.
  • Main Legion of Super-Heroes characters: Blok, Brainiac 5, Invisible Kid and Sun Boy.
  • Flashback Legion of Super-Heroes characters: Cosmic Boy, Lightning Lad and Saturn Girl.
  • All other 30th Century characters have cameo flashback appearances.
  • Superman mentions meeting Superboy of Earth-Prime during the Crisis events. However, that Superboy "...went off into limbo."
  • This cover is a homage of the cover of Fantastic Four #249 also drawn by John Byrne.
  • Story continues from Legion of Super-Heroes #37.
  • Story continues in Action Comics #591.

description:
Guess Who's In Metropolis...?!

"To Laugh and Die in Metropolis!" Story by John Byrne. Art by John Byrne and Karl Kesel. Tired of trading blows with that sour-puss Batman, the Clown Prince of Crime makes his way to Metropolis. However, the Joker just can't seem to fathom why the Man of Steel can't see the humor in this move. Meanwhile, billion dollar miscreant Lex Luthor sets out to prove that anybody can be bought, for the right price.

Notes:

  • The Superman Robot was created by the Joker.
  • First appearance of Toby Raynes.
  • A teaser that will lead into the events of Millennium.
  • Lex Luthor states that he owns 90% of the state.
  • Ranked #12 in Wizard Magazine's list of "100 Best Single Issue Comics Since You Were Born".

Notes:

  • Rampage cameo flashback appearance.

description:
As Mr. Mxyzptlk comes to this dimension to challenge Superman. All Superman has to do is get Mxyzptlk to say his name backwards to get him to return to his own dimension.

Notes:

  • The first post-Crisis appearance of Mr. Mxyzptlk.
  • Mr. Mxyzptlk took the identity of a man named Ben DeRoy.
  • Ben DeRoy is an anagram and a homage to Marvel's Beyonder.
  • Old Man Superman, Fat Superman, (Ugly) Weird Superman and (Large Head) Strange Superman were homages of the Silver Age Superman.

description:
Marking the one-year anniversary death of Lori Lemaris (later revealed as a lie) Clark and Ronald prepare a memorial for Lori in the form of a song of poetry. Clark tells the story of his first love to the poet. He'd met Lori in college when her wheelchair sped down a hill, which he stopped by using his laser beam on the wheels. She flung into his arms and it was love at first sight. They went on dates but Lori always cut them short. Clark felt hopelessly in love and proposed but Lori couldn't accept. She knew about his powers and she herself also had a big secret that would make a union between them impossible.

Notes:

  • "Dedicated to the memory of Wayne Boring, the first Lori artist"
  • The first appearance of Lori Lemaris and Ronal in the post-Crisis universe.
  • Aquaman, Jimmy Olsen, Lois Lane, Allie and Whit cameo flashback appearances.
  • A teaser that will lead into the events of Millennium.
name: Lost Love

description:
Millennium: Week 2. "Toys in the Attic!" John Byrne gives one of the Man of Steel's oldest enemies in upgrade in this Millennium tie-in issue. The Toyman has never been this dangerous before. Plus, Lana Lang...a Manhunter? Say it isn't so. It's a mystery that leads Superman back to where it all began...back to Smallville.

Notes:

  • First post-Crisis appearance of the Toyman.
  • British Intelligence MI7 appears.
  • Morgan Edge appears as a shadowy silhouette on page 18 panel 5.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #436, Action Comics #596 and Millennium #2.

description:
Millennium: Week 6. "Last Stand!" Guest-starring Green Lantern (Hal Jordan). Two of Earth's greatest champions, Superman and Green Lantern, have traveled to the far side of the universe in search of the missing Guardians. What they find is the most powerful Manhunter of all, the Manhunter Highmaster! Can even the Man of Steel and the greatest Green Lantern of all stand against such an awesome power?

Notes:

  • Most characters have cameo flashback appearances.
  • Story continues in Millennium #7.

description:
"Wings!" Children are disappearing all over Metropolis, and Superman intends to find out why. But when some of the children turn up horribly mutated, even the Man of Steel is taken aback by the macabre circumstances of this case.

Notes:

  • The first post-Crisis appearance of Mrs. Sarah Olsen.

description:
"He only Laughs when I Hurt!" Superman can change the course of mighty rivers, turn mountains into dust, and stymied the destructive course of hot-liquid magma. Yet, he just can't seem to contend with the whimsical Prankster. Meanwhile, a starling discovery is made on the frozen continent of Antarctica.

Notes:

  • The first post-Crisis appearance of the Prankster.
  • The first actual appearance of Morgan Edge.
  • The first appearance of Matrix.
  • Darkseid is actually Desaad in disguise.

description:
"Cries in the Night!" The screaming terror known as the Silver Banshee has returned and she's got revenge on her mind. How can Superman hope to defeat his enemy when his own super-hearing makes him even more susceptible to her powers than anybody? Maybe with a little help from the Batman?

Notes:

  • Superman appears briefly wearing Batman's uniform.

description:
"Return to Krypton!" Guest-starring Hawkman and Hawkwoman. In order to save his life, Superman must return to the one place he never thought he'd see - the planet Krypton. Here the Man of Steel will embark on a much needed sojourn. Once done, the Last Son of Krypton will have a better understanding of who he is, where he comes from, and his place in the universe.

Notes:

  • "With Johnny DC" 2/3 page text piece by Johnny DC featuring DC Comics related news and information. Plus, "DC Checklist This Week" containing the comics that were issued for the week of February 16, 1988.
  • The story continues from Action Comics #600.
name: Return to Krypton

description:
"The Power That Failed!" Part 1 of 2. For some inexplicable reason Superman's powers - strength, flight, speed, invulnerability, and vision - begin to fail him. How can the Man of Steel hope to survive an all out attack by the new menacing duo of Psi-Phon and the hulking Dreadnaught? Meanwhile, a strange new visitor who bares a striking resemblance to a fallen heroine, makes her way toward Smallville. Plus, Lex Luthor gets a new hand (his hand was amputated due to Kryptonite radiation poisoning - see Action Comics #600).

Notes:

  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #442.
  • First appearances of Professor Thaddeus Killgrave, Dreadnaught and Psi-Phon.

description:
Men of Steel! Guest-Starring The Doom Patrol!

A strange new visitor who bares a striking resemblance to a fallen heroine, arrives in Smallville. The robotic menace known as Metallo is back and he's in complete control of the Doom Patrol's strongest member, Robotman. Now, Superman and the all new Doom Patrol must find a way to defeat these super powered robots before someone really gets hurt.

Notes:

  • On page 7 panel 5 read the story in "Doom Patrol #10 before you read any further!"
  • A homage to Terry Austin and Paul Kupperberg on page 11 panel 2.
  • Paul Kupperberg credited as "Paul Kupperberg - kibitzing."
  • A Baron Sunday teaser.
  • Lex Luthor cameo flashback appearance.
  • A letter to the editor from T. M. Maple.

description:
"The Supergirl Saga" part 1 of 3! Who is this new Supergirl? Where did she come from? What is the secret of her powers? And what does Lex Luthor have to do with all this?

Notes:

  • Lex Luthor, Pete Ross and Lana Lang from the Pocket Universe appear.
  • Lex Luthor and Lana Lang of post-Crisis universe appear.
  • Flashback to The Greatest Hero of Them All storyline.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #444.

description:
"The Supergirl Saga" part 3. When Superman encounters a trio of powerful villains who've murdered on a planetary level, will he do the unthinkable? Can the Last Son make the decision to become judge, jury, and executioner?

Notes:

  • Bruce Wayne, Hal Jordan, Oliver Queen, Pete Ross and Lex Luthor of the Pocket Universe are killed by the Pocket Universe Phantom Zone Criminals.
  • General Zod, Quex-Ul and Zaora of the Pocket Universe are killed by Superman.
  • Smallville of the Pocket Universe and post-Crisis universe appears.
  • Story continues from Adventures of Superman #444.

description:
Can even Superman survive when his two greatest adversaries--Lex Luthor and Brainiac--team up to destroy him once and for all? Can these two arch-villains play nice long enough to accomplish the task at hand?

Luthor has Brainiac under his control, Brainiac has Superman under his control... just another day in Metropolis!

Notes:

  • Cover dated Winter 1988.
  • "With a big thanks to that adventurous lad, Jerry Ordway, for all the advice and input."
  • Allie, Whit, Lois Lane, Perry White, Lex Luthor and Lex Luthor's Warsuit appear in a dream sequence.

description:
Invasion: First Strike! "...It's just a Shot Away!" Part 1 of 2. Guest-starring Captain Atom, Gangbuster, and the Guardian. A series of voodoo deaths is plaguing the city of Metropolis, and the Man of Steel has just gone MIA. Hopefully the vigilante known as Gangbuster can stop this mysterious menace before it's too late. Plus, an alien armada has begun a full scale invasion of the planet Earth (see Invasion! #1-3).

Notes:

  • Cover dated Winter 1988.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #449.

description:
Invasion: Aftermath! "Of Course, You Know, This Means War!" Part 1 of 2. Guest-starring Gangbuster and the Guardian. One is a fully deputized officer of the law. The other is a tough as nails take the law into his own hands vigilante. Can't imagine why these two can't get along. It's Gangbuster vs. the Guardian in a no holds barred thriller!

Notes:

  • Most characters have cameo flashback appearances.
  • The letter column title is changed to "Superman the Letter Column."
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #450.

description:
Superman in Exile. Part 1 of 13. In light of recent events - Superman's execution of three super powerful criminals, his mind's tampering by Brainiac, and his schizophrenic behavior as Gangbuster (see Superman #22 and 25-27) - and fearing he may harm the very people he has sworn to protect - Superman begins a self-imposed exile into deep space. The Last Son of Krypton soon learns that there are dangers out here in the void the likes of which he's never dreamed of.

Notes:

  • Cover signed "Gammill/Janke after Steranko."
  • Gillespie is not seen but is on the phone with Morgan Edge.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #451.

description:
Superman in Exile. Part 3 of 13. "If this be My Fate!" When Superman comes across yet another dead world he realizes that Hfuhruhurr, the World Bringer has committed another horrendous act. This time the Man of Steel intends to see that this villain meets with righteous justice. Dan Jurgens returns for the sequel to his and Jim Starlin's World Bringer saga from the pages of Adventures of Superman Annual #1.

Notes:

  • "And a tip of the sombrero to Jerry Ordway for plot assistance."
  • The cover is a homage to the cover of Action Comics #300.
  • Story continued from Adventures of Superman #451.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #452.

description:
Superman in Exile. Part 5 of 13. "Alone!" One step closer to finding redemption, Superman continues his self-imposed exile in deep space. Plus, in the Man of Steel's absence, Lex Luthor plans his biggest coup yet in "Hostile Takeover: King of All he Surveys!" Part 1 of 4.

Notes:

  • "Alone!" written by Roger Stern, penciled by Kerry Gammill, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by John Costanza and colored by Glenn Whitmore.
  • "King of All he Surveys!" written by Roger Stern, penciled by Dan Jurgens, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by Albert De Guzman, colored by Glenn Whitmore and with thanks to Jerry Ordway.
  • Superman, Matrix, Martha and Jonathan Kent appear in the story "Alone!".
  • All other characters except for Lex Luthor appear as cameo flashback appearances in the story "King of All he Surveys!".
  • Story continued from Adventures of Superman #452.
  • Both stories continue in Adventures of Superman #453.

description:
"Mr. Mxyzptlk! in As Good as His Word!". An all Lex Luthor issue! That mischievous imp, Mr. Mxyzptlk, is back in Metropolis. With the Man of Steel in a self-imposed exile in deep space who will stop him. Well, Lex Luthor has never been one to share his city. Plus, Luthor's Machiavellian scheming continues in "Hostile Takeover: Poison Pill!" Part 3 of 4.

Notes:

  • "As Good as His Word!" written by Roger Stern and Tom Peyer, penciled by Paris Cullins, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by John Costanza and colored by Glenn Whitmore.
  • "Poison Pill!" written by Jerry Ordway, penciled by Dan Jurgens, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by Albert De Guzman and colored by Glenn Whitmore.
  • Superman doesn't appear in this issue, however Mr. Mxyzptlk briefly takes the identity of Superman to scare Lex Luthor.
  • Laura Conway is not seen but is heard calling Morgan Edge on the phone.
  • The "Hostile Takeover" storyline is continued from Adventures of Superman #453.
  • The "Hostile Takeover" storyline continues in Adventures of Superman #454.
name: As Good As His Word! / Poison Pill!

description:
Superman in Exile. Part 10 of 13. "Gladiator!" Superman battles the hulking tyrant, Mongul to the death in the arena.

Notes:

  • Matrix appears as Clark Kent.
  • Jerry Ordway and George Perez credited as co-conspirators.
  • Story continued from Action Comics Annual #2.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #455.

description:
Superman in Exile. Part 12 of 13. "Two Destinies!" The old cleric probes the Last Son of Krypton's mind with the Kryptonian Eradicator (remember that name - it's a name that will come back to haunt the Man of Steel), and gets him one step closer to redemption.

Notes:

  • Mr. Mxyzptlk, Brainiac, Lex Luthor, Silver Banshee, Klerik, Jimmy Olsen, Lois Lane, Lana Lang, Kryptonite Ring, Superman Signal Watch, Krypton, Kal-El's Spacecraft, Daily Planet, Gangbuster's Symbol and an unknown character appear on page 10 panel 6.
  • General Zod, Quex-Ul, Zaora, Batman, Mr. Miracle, Guy Gardner, Ice, Blue Beetle, Booster Gold, Superman and two unknown heroes on page 18 panel 5.
  • Matrix appears as Clark Kent.
  • The last letter column titled "Superman the Letter Column."
  • Story continued from Adventures of Superman #455.
  • Story concludes in Adventures of Superman #456.

description:
"Visions of Grandeur" Cameo by Darkseid. And, "The Racer's Edge." In this double feature, Brainiac and Lex Luthor return to plague the Man of Steel. Plus, Morgan Edge is paid a visit by the Black Racer of the New Gods.

Notes:

  • "Visions of Grandeur" written by Jerry Ordway, penciled by Curt Swan, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by John Costanza, colored by Glenn Whitmore and braintrust by Roger Stern.
  • "The Racer's Edge" written by Jerry Ordway, penciled by Kerry Gammill, inked by Dennis Janke, lettered by John Costanza, colored by Glenn Whitmore and inspiration by Jack Kirby.
  • Both stories are running concurrently. The top half of the page is the story "Visions of Grandeur" and the bottom half of the page is the story "The Racer's Edge."
  • Superman only appears as a hallucination in the story "Visions of Grandeur."
  • Desaad is impersonating Darkseid in the story "The Racer's Edge."
  • Right half of the cover is a homage to the cover of Superman #167.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #458.

description:
"Laugh...I thought I'd Die!" Guest-starring the Guardian. The Prankster's back, and unless the Man of Steel can get to the hospital on time, Morgan Edge may not survive the goofy villain's latest practical joke.

Notes:

  • On pages 2-3 panel 4 Kirby Salvage is a homage to Jack Kirby.
  • Cameo flashback appearances of Thanagarians, Lex Luthor, Baron Sunday and Jimmy Olsen as Elastic Lad.
  • Superman appears as Gangbuster in a cameo flashback appearance.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #459.
name: Laugh... I Thought I'd Die!

description:
"Best Friends!" Guest-starring the Guardian and the Newsboy Legion. Superman attempts to help Jimmy Olsen with his altered genetic make-up problem, but his "pal" is having no part of it.

Notes:

  • Cameo headshots of Sarah Olsen, Cat Grant, Perry White and Husque.
  • Cover is a homage of Superman's Pal Jimmy Olsen #133.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #460.

description:
Unnatural Disasters!" Guest-starring the Guardian and the Newsboy Legion. A startling change comes over Jimmy Olsen, and it just maybe his "pal's" fault. Meanwhile, an enormous tsunami threatens to engulf the city of Metropolis. This looks like a job for Superman!

Notes:

  • On page 20 panel 1 the restaurant is called Neptune Perkin's Seafood which is a homage to Neptune Perkins.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #461.

description:
"Jimmy Olsen's Excellent Adventure!" Jimmy Olsen is trapped in a strange parallel dimension, and it's up to Superman and a stranger with amazing abilities to find the youth and bring him home safely. But, does Olsen want to come back when he finds the one person he's been searching for his whole life?

Notes:

  • The title of the story is a parody and homage to the movie Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure.
  • Contains a brief history of James Olsen Sr.
  • Clark Kent accepts the position of managing editor at Newstime Magazine.
  • 16 page "Lightning Racers" promotional insert.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #462.

description:
The Day of the Krypton Man. Part 1 of 6. "The Nature of the Beast!" Guest-starring Lobo. Cameo by the Guardian. Superman safeguards the Kryptonite shards he procured from Bloodsport in a secret location in the Antarctic. Jimmy gets counseling from the Guardian. Lobo is hired to kill the Man of Steel, and an alien from Superman's recent past heads to Earth in search of revenge. Plus, the Main Man meets Bibbo!

Notes:

  • Cameo headshot appearances of James Olsen Sr., Mokkari and Simyan.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #464.

description:
The Day of the Krypton Man. Part 4 of 6. "Krypton Man" Draaga has finally found the Last Son of Krypton. Revenge is within his grasp, but here on Earth Superman is at full strength. It's not a good day to be a revenge seeking alien.

Notes:

  • Lex Luthor, Lois Lane and Combattor cameo flashback appearances.
  • The cover is a homage to the covers of Crack Comics #36 and The Incredible Hulk #1.
  • Story continued from Action Comics #651.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #465.

description:
"The Evil Factory!" Guest-starring the Guardian. The Evil Factory unveils their latest creation...a clone of the Man of Steel. And it's completely under their command. Introducing the Kryptonite Man. Can anyone stand against this seemingly unstoppable force?

Notes:

  • Clark Kent is rehired by the Daily Planet as a freelance journalist.
  • Cameo flashback appearances of the Four Armed Terror, Number One and James Olsen Sr.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #466.

description:
"Native Sons!" A Native American shaman has makes his way to Smallville seeking to halt the spread of pollution by the Industrial Nation. Plus, Superman reveals to Lana Lang that he and Lois Lane have begun a romantic relationship. She does not take the news very well. Includes the 8-page insert "Jimmy Olsen's Diary!"

Notes:

  • Lucy Lane and James Olsen Sr. appear as photos in Jimmy Olsen's scrapbook.
  • "Jimmy Olsen's Diary!" "A Special Superman Extra!" "art, script, etc. by Jerry Ordway."
  • Jimmy Olsen's scrapbook begins with the first appearance of Superman saving the space plane Constitution to when Jimmy was no longer a friend of Superman.
  • This issue contains 40 pages.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #468.

description:
"The World of Tomorrow!" Guest-starring Jade and Obsidian. Tobias Manning (the Terra Man) and his Terramen have returned, but this time they're not just facing the Man of Steel. The children of Alan Scott (the Golden Age Green Lantern), Jade and Obsidian, are at the scene to lend a hand.

Notes:

  • Cameo flashback appearance of Infinity Inc. members.
  • Daniel Hall cameo flashback appearance.
  • First post-Crisis appearances of Terra-Man and Terry Dean.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #469.

description:
Soul Search. Part 2 of 3. "Lives in the Balance!" Guest-starring the Black Racer and Gangbuster. Superman will batter down the very gates of Hell to save Jimmy and Jerry's mortal souls. Plus, a startling secret is revealed about the past between Perry White's wife and Lex Luthor.

Notes:

  • Brief history of the Lex Luthor and Alice Spencer (White) affair.
  • Lex Luthor once owned the Daily Planet.
  • Perry White finds out that Jerry White is not his son.
  • Story continues from Action Comics #656.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #470.

description:
Krisis of the Krimson Kryptonite. Part 1 of 4. "Lex Luthor: Triumphant!" Lex Luthor is dying, but he won't allow that to happen until he has destroyed the Man of Steel once and for all. Enter: Mr. Mxyzptlk and Red Kryptonite. Using this mysterious ruby colored rock, Luthor makes Superman his physical equal. Now, let the best man win.

Notes:

  • Clark Kent wrote a novel called The Janus Contract. This book was on the reduced prices table.
  • Lois Lane made the comment "Don't be glum. You're in good company -- Stephen King, J.L. Byrne..."
  • Last .75 cent issue.
  • Story continues in Adventures of Superman #472.

description:
Krisis of the Krimson Kryptonite. Part 4 of 4. Special Extra-Sized issue. "The Human Factor!" Cameos by the Guardian and Gangbuster. Superman has been rendered powerless, beaten and humiliated by his arch nemesis, Lex Luthor. But when Luthor's own arrogance causes him to break the rules of the game set forth by Mr. Mxyzptlk, can a fully restored Man of Steel be far behind? Plus, Lois Lane gives Clark Kent her answer to his marriage proposal.

Notes:

  • This issue features a humorous cameo by Marvel's First Family - the Fantastic Four.
  • The cover of this issue is said to have been a tribute to the George Reeves version of Superman.
  • Cameo flashback appearance by Barrage and Emil Hamilton.
  • Martha Kent is not seen but is on the phone with Clark Kent.
  • 48 page issue.
  • Story continues from Action Comics #659.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #473.

description:
"Mister Z!" Who is the mysterious Mr. Z? Can Superman find out the answer to that very question before he ends up spending eternity in imprisonment?

Notes:

  • First $1.00 issue.
  • First appearance of the triangle chronological order system.
  • Mr. Z takes the name George Bailey as an alias.
  • Triangle 1991 #1.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #660.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #474.

description:
The Name, Pardners, is Terra-Man!" The ecological terrorist Terra-Man is back and LexCorp is going to pay. This time Manning crosses the line and an innocent man pays the price. Can Superman stop him before Lois becomes the next victim in Terra-Man's war on corporate America?

Notes:

  • Triangle 1991 #4.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #661.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #475.

description:
The Man of Steel has always stood for "Truth, Justice, and the American Way," but will he step into the realm of world politics when the government requests that he forcibly oust a foreign dictator from office?

Plus, in the wake of Clark Kent revealing his duel identity to Lois (see Action Comics #662), Mrs. Lane must now sort out what it means to be the wife of Superman.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1991 #7.

description:
"Time and Time Again" part 3 "The Warsaw Ghetto!". The Man of Steel battles the Third Reich after the nigh omnipotent Spectre transports Superman back in time to the days of World War II.

The Man of Steel battles the Third Reich in this time spanning epic. The nigh omnipotent Spectre has transported Superman back in time to the days of World War II to confront an enemy from his past (see Superman #51 for Mr. Z's 1st app.). Plus, the back-up tale "Attack of the D.N.Alien!" Part 1 of 2. Starring the Guardian and the Newsboy Legion.

Notes:

  • "The Warsaw Ghetto" written and penciled by Jerry Ordway, inked by Dennis Janke, colored by Glenn Whitmore and lettered by John Costanza.
  • "Attack of the D.N.Alien!" written, penciled and inked by Karl Kesel, colored by Glenn Whitmore and lettered by Bill Oakley.
  • Mr. Z takes the alias General Zeiten.
  • Triangle 1991 #10.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #663.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #477.

description:
"Time and Time Again" part 6. Superman continues his adventure through time, fighting side-by-side with the vicious Demon to save the legendary Kingdom of Camelot.

Time and Time Again! Phase 6. "Camelot!" Guest-starring Etrigan, the Demon. Cameo by the Shining Knight. Superman continues his adventure through time. In this chapter the Man of Steel must fight side-by-side with the vicious Demon to save the legendary Kingdom of Camelot. Story concludes in Adventures of Superman #478. Plus, the back-up tale "Blaze of Glory!" Part 2 of 2. Starring the Guardian and the Newsboy Legion.

Notes:

  • "Camelot" written, penciled and inked by Jerry Ordway, colored by Glenn Whitmore and lettered by John Costanza.
  • "Blaze of Glory!" written, penciled and inked by Karl Kesel, colored by Glenn Whitmore, lettered by Bill Oakley and "soul and inspiration" by Jack Kirby.
  • Triangle 1991 #13.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #664.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #478.

description:
"Red Glass!" Part 1 of 3. Superman suddenly finds himself in a world where all his arch villains have been slain...by him. And the public at large lives in fear of what he may do next. Can the Man of Steel solve this mystery and find out what is happening before it's too late? Story continues in Adventures of Superman #479. Plus, the back-up tale "Charlie & Company!" Starring the Guardian and the Newsboy Legion.

Notes:

  • "Breaking Up" written by James D. Hudvall, penciled by Ed Hannigan, inked by Willie Blyberg, colored by Glenn Whitmore and lettered by John Costanza.
  • "Charlie & Company" written, penciled and inked by Karl Kesel, colored by Glenn Whitmore and lettered by Bill Oakley.
  • "Superman's Day of Wrath" takes place on April 15, 1998.
  • Triangle 1991 #16.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #665.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #479.

description:
The Mark of the Krypton Man! Part 1 of 3. Featuring the 1st appearance of the Eradicator (in anthropoid form). A powerful being with ties to Superman's past decides that the Last Son of Krypton is not living up to his heritage, and decides to recreate a dead world here on Earth.

  1. Pages 1-7 penciled by Dan Jurgens and inked by Brett Breeding.
  2. Pages 8-9, 14-16 and 25 penciled by Bob McLeod and inked by Denis Rodier.
  3. Pages 10-13 and 22-23 penciled by Jon Bogdanove and inked by Dennis Janke.
  4. Pages 17-21 penciled and inked by Art Thibert.
  5. Pages 24, 26-30 penciled by Tom Grummett and inked by Jerry Ordway.
  6. Pages 31-38 penciled by Dan Jurgens and inked by Bob McLeod.

Notes:

  • Cameo flashback appearances of the Klerik and Elastic Lad.
  • Jimmy Olsen is laid off at the Daily Planet.
  • 48 page issue.
  • Triangle 1991 #20.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #1.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #480.

"Fangs of the Bloodhounds!" Guest-starring the Guardian. Superman is a being with abilities far beyond those of ordinary men. This is a fact that makes some people very nervous. If the Man of Steel ever were to turn on mankind, who would be there to keep him in check. Meet the Watchdogs!

Notes:

  • Cameo flashback appearance of Superman as Gangbuster.
  • Triangle 1991 #24.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #2.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #481.

description:
"Superman's Fiancee, Lois Lane!" A secret cabal gathers to discuss items that pertain to the death of an innocent man. Plus, this issue explores what it's like to be the fiancee of the most powerful and busiest super hero on Earth. Includes a 5-page excerpt from the Daily Planet by Lois Lane.

Notes:

  • Five pages of the Daily Planet newspaper dated Friday July 28 1991 are included at the end of the story.
  • Triangle 1991 #28.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #3.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #482.

description:
Clark Kent sets out to shut down Intergang once and for all. But when a Boom Tube from Apokolips shows up this turns into a job...for Superman.

Clark Kent sets out to shut down Intergang once and for all. But when a Boom Tube from Apokolips shows up this turns into a job for Superman! Plus, introducing a new force for good who just may turn out to be the back up Superman needs at the right time.

Notes:

  • The first appearance of Agent Liberty.
  • Triangle 1991 #32.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #4.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #483.

description:
"Time and Time Again, Again!" Guest-starring the Metal Men. Superman has a tough decision to make. Is the mysterious Waverider attempting to destroy the time stream, or is he out to save many innocent lives from certain death. With the Linear Men hot on the golden time-traveler's trail, the Man of Steel does not have long to make up his mind.

Notes:

  • Adolph Hitler and Linear Man cameo flashback appearances.
  • Triangle 1991 #36.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #5.

description:
"Blackout" part 4. With the Man of Steel MIA, it's up to Gangbuster, Agent of Liberty and Thorn to keep the city safe for the citizens of Metropolis until his return.

Black Out! Part 4 of 5. "Wedding Daze!" Guest-starring the Guardian, Gangbuster, Agent of Liberty and Thorn. With the Man of Steel MIA, it's up to Gangbuster, Agent of Liberty and Thorn to keep the city safe for the citizens of Metropolis until his return. Meanwhile, star investigative reporter Lois Lane, Professor Hamilton and the Guardian search for her missing fiancee.

Notes:

  • "- - with special thanks to story-meister Dennis Janke!"
  • A 16 page free insert for Sonic the Hedgehog.
  • Triangle 1991 #40.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #6.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #485.

description:
When the Atlantis/Oumland War spills over and threatens the surface world Superman decides it's time to get involved, with or without the Lord of the Seven Seas blessing.

Clark and Cat are out on a ship surveying the seas for a story Cat is planning to report on. A possible outbreak of war between Atlantis and Oumland is brewing. While on board they are attacked by a Plesiosaur and fall overboard. Superman and Aquaman work together to fight the creature but are interrupted by torpedoes headed towards Atlantis. They go after the torpedoes, while Superman is taking hold of one he crashes it into a the side of a rock and is injured, it is then that he gets help from someone dear in his past.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #2.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #7.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #486.
name: Shadows from the Past!

description:
"Metropolis Mailbag!" Special guest-appearance by Bruce Wayne (Batman). In this special Christmas issue, Superman spends the night reading letters from around the world asking for his help. Though the Last Son of Krypton can bend steel with his bare hands, change the course of mighty rivers, and leap tall buildings in a single bound, there are still some things even a Superman can't do. Get the tissues ready, this one pulls at the heart strings.

Notes:

  • Lana Lang cameo headshot appearance.
  • Triangle 1992 #6.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #8.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #487.

description:
"Panic in the Sky" part 2. Even Superman can't stand alone against the power of Warworld. So the Man of Steel gathers the toughest group of super-heroes ever assembled, Dirty Dozen-style, but will even they be enough to stop this new threat?

The cosmically astute Metron has visited Almerac. He is speechless to see the civilisation reduced to ruins by Warworld's attack. He is musing when he is suddenly attacked telepathically by Brainiac. He is captured but manages to teleport his Mobius Chair to Earth.

Meanwhile, Dubbilex, Superman and Guardian are removing the debris inside Project Cadmus when the Mobius Chair appears. Dubbilex senses that something sinister has befallen Metron. While they are at this, the Gods Orion and Lightray appear in search of Metron. Superman informs them that Warworld has captured Metron. They leave for Warworld without heeding to Superman's warnings.

Upon Warworld, Orion and Lightray are quickly subdued by, Supergirl, Maxima and other warriors.

Superman is telepathically mocked by Brainiac. He realises that he will need the help of other heroes to win this battle. So he contacts Lex Luthor for equipment and then goes out in search of others.

Superman requests Deathstroke to be his team's field leader, meets Diana and Aquaman and then broadcasts the news all over the World. Heroes assemble from all over the World to listen to Superman.

Meanwhile, Aquaman is attacked underwater by Brainiac's Headship and captured. The Headship appears outside the Heroes' headquarters with him.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #10.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #9.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #488.

description:
"Panic in the Sky" part 6. It's the final battle for the fate of mankind. The heroes of Earth press the attack to confront Warworld once and for all, but Brainiac's final solution may prove the deadliest attack of all.

Warworld’s hordes are arriving in large numbers. Batman’s ground unit is doing its best to keep them at bay. Prof. Hamilton has rigged up a dispersal cannon. He and Luthor fire it at the hordes. Jimmy wonders what is happening inside Warworld.

Maxima pledges to fight beside the heroes, because Brainiac has treated her like a slave. Superman does not want her help, because he knows her nature. She has been trouble from the first day she has appeared on Earth. Kilowog and Wonder Woman say that Maxima would never make a sacrifice like Draaga. Maxima is insulted and gears up for attack. But Deathstroke stops them, saying that they have a more important mission. Superman has already used his x-ray vision to isolate three access routes to reach Brainiac. Agent Liberty says that they should split into three groups. Deathstroke puts himself, Metron and Superman in charge of one group each. Maxima wants to join them but Superman denies her permission. She keeps Guy and the Metal-Men in charge of her safe-keeping.

The three groups head for Brainiac from three different sides. Flash has been given the responsibility to breach Brainiac’s defenses. But he does not achieve his goal. Brainiac uses electricity to knock him out. Then he unleashes the most powerful weapon on Warworld, himself. Brainiac uses the “Augmentation System” to magnify his telepathic powers a thousand times, unleashing what appears to be a “psychic death radiation”. The heroes are forced to retreat and many civilians caught in the radius of the radiation disintegrate. Brainiac has built an impenetrable force-field around himself.

Next, Brainiac deploys hovering discs over Metropolis. The discs interconnect to form an unbreakable energy-grid, which even the heroes’ laser-rifles cannot destroy.

Back on Warworld, Superman says that their groups are no match for Brainiac’s power. Dubbilex warns them that Brainiac has already initiated his plan of reducing Metropolis to table-top size. Superman orders a suicide mission to stop Brainiac.

Maxima plays Guy and the Metal-Men to allow her a chance to attack Brainiac. She is surprised that Guy is taking orders from Superman. Guy is insulted and offers to free Maxima for help in taking down Brainiac. He uses his ring to create a pathway to the central chamber for Maxima and the Metal-Men. The operation is partially successful. Maxima is undamaged but the Metal-Men have obviously taken the radiation hit. But even Maxima falls before Brainiac’s psychic power. Flash plays a desperate gamble. He picks up a shard of glass and hurls it towards the cables connecting Brainiac to Warworld. Maxima takes the chance. She attacks a now diminished Brainiac.

Some of the heroes appear on earth via a boom tube and crush the energy-discs, thus breaking up the energy grid.

Brainiac tries a last chance to save himself from Maxima. He crawls with death-like slowness and is successful in ejecting a sphere outside of Warworld. Maxima is stopped by Superman. But Brainiac is lobotomized. His brain is gone.

Notes:

  • The title of the story is a homage to the DC Comics war series Our Army at War.
  • Triangle 1992 #14.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #10.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #489.

description:
Panic in the Sky! Epilogue. "Another Panic in the Sky!" In the aftermath of Earth's epic battle with Warworld, is Superman in any shape to beat back the cosmic planet-scavengers who swarm in Warworld's wake? Can Lex Luthor prevail where the Man of Steel has failed?

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #18.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #11.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #490.

description:
Slade Wilson is a wanted man. Now, the Man of Steel sets out to bring down one of the most dangerous men alive!

"Sins of the Father!" Part 1 of 2. Guest-starring Deathstroke. Slade Wilson is a wanted man (see Deathstroke the Terminator #1-5 for why). Now, the Man of Steel sets out to bring down one of the most dangerous men alive! Get ready for a game of cat and mouse the likes of which has never been seen before.

Notes:

  • The story continues in Deathstroke the Terminator #12.
  • Triangle 1992 #22.

description:
Superman spends the night reading letters from around the world asking for his help. Though the Last Son of Krypton can bend steel with his bare hands, change the course of mighty rivers, and leap tall buildings in a single bound, there are still some things even a Superman can't do.

"Raising the Stakes!" Guest-starring Robin. Jimmy Olsen's girlfriend has fallen into the thrall of a vampire. Can Superman, his pal, and the Boy Wonder find Lucy and save the poor girl's soul before it's too late?

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #30.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #14.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #493.

description:
Superman will stand idly by no more after witnessing the injustices felt by one woman at the hands of her abusive husband. Not even the law can stop the Man of Steel!

Crisis at Hand. Part 2 of 2. "Rage!" Superman was forced by law to stand by powerless and helpless to prevent the abuse of a woman by her abusive husband. But he can't stand idly by any longer. This 2-part tale takes look at the serious and an all too real problem of spousal abuse.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #38.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #16.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #495.

description:
Doomsday: Prologue. "Time Ryders!" Waverider and the Linear Men have always been at odds about how to monitor the time stream. But the unexpected happens when the Linear Men actually ask the golden time-traveler to join their team. But can Superman stand idly by while the Linear Men possess this much power over time? Does he have a choice? Plus, on the last page, powerful pounding fists are the harbinger of quite possibly the most dangerous threat the Earth has ever faced, and the issue ends with the ominous warning "...Doomsday is coming!"

Notes:

  • Triangle 1992 #42.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #17.

description:
SUPERMAN is here to save the day, But will he. As Superman comes to aid the Justice League he has his first confrontation with the destructive DOOMSDAY. Will Superman and the Justice league defeat this monster?! Will they be defeated and leave the world to the devastating Doomsday?! Read this issue to find Out!!!!

Notes:

  • The story continues from Justice League America #69.
  • Triangle 1992 #46.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #18.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #497.

description:
Superman #75 is the famous issue where Superman is killed by Doomsday. Each page is a full page shot of the intense battle. Superman and Doomsday just exchange blows one after another. Superman eventually defeats Doomsday at the cost of his own life.

Black Bag (Memorial Collector's Edition)

It is a Direct Market Memorial Collector's Edition. The comic comes in a black polybag with a trading card, poster, stamps, Daily Planet Obituary & black mourning armband included inside the sealed bag.

Black Bag (Platinum Edition)

Retailer exclusive. This version was not available to the same commercial outlets as anyone could sell normal comics, this certain comic was retailer protected.

*Contents need to be confirmed if the same as the standard Memorial Collector's Edition.

description:
The JLA arrive in Metropolis and read letters from people needing help--just as Superman once did. Heroes and everyday citizens alike try to come together to cope with Superman's death.

Superman is dead? Actually no, he's being reanimated/regenerated but no one knows about this. This issue begins on Christmas Eve. Various heroes are there and Captain Marvel arrives. Ironically it is raining not snowing. Aquaman likes it and Green Lantern does too. Nightwing can't believe it and the new Robin Tim Drake in a moment out of character decides not to remark for fear of sounding like an idiot (huh?). So since Superman is dead the heroes decide to get down to business whatever that may be at this point.

We then see a kid named Mitch whose house was destroyed in a fight between Superman and Doomsday in Ohio where we all know Superman's creators were raised (Ohio). Mitch must have run away from home since he is seen walking the streets of Metropolis. Poor Mitch he feels its his fault Superman died. Some wacko has a press conference and says she is Mrs. Superman and that they lived in a New York penthouse and had vacations all over the world and he took her there to protect her from his enemies. We all know it is bull and Lois Lane and Jimmy Olsen are there too. Of course we know it's a lie.

Lois leaves and Jimmy sees Mitch. They talk for a bit and Mitch wants to talk to someone who knew Superman and Jimmy takes him to Bibbo's to eat. We follow Lois who heads to Clark's apartment of course she is mourning over the loss of Clark. She opens the door and cries of course but also there are Ma and Pa Kent. They came to settle Clark's things in order as well as Lana Lang.

We head over to the Metropolis Post Office. Every Christmas, Superman would read the mail sent to him and try to make miracles happen. This is the business the heroes will try to do in Superman's absence. Of course, Guy Gardner scoffs at the idea and Wonder Woman puts him in his place. There are letters for Superman to help find hidden cities and gold. There is even a letter from a lady who is terminally ill who wants Superman to find her lost son of over 30 years. For once Guy Gardner does something nice and he takes that case. Wonder Woman reads a letter from a woman whose house was destroyed she just wanted to thank him for saving her family's lives. So they agree to put out a helping hand.

Back at Bibbo's restaurant Jimmy and Mitch are eating and sitting with Bibbo and talking. Jimmy finally remembers Mitch from being in the news due to Superman and Doomsday fight that destroyed his house. He still is feeling like it's his fault and Bibbo does his best to make him feel better. Bibbo gives Mitch air fare to get home. Back at Clark's place Lana decides its best the world should know Clark and Superman are one and the same. Eventually though they decide to stay quiet about Clark's private life thanks to the calmness of Pa Kent's urging.

Wonder Woman reaches a apartment of a Roger Anderson. I guess he is Mitch's dad. Wonder Women tells him about his wife and kids and their house destroyed by Doomsday.

The story splits up as the heroes are doing what they can. Jimmy takes Mitch to Superman's memorial site. Green Lantern and Flash are building Mitch's mom a new house, talk about Christmas miracles. Wonder Woman brings Mitch's dad to the new house and apparently things will work out and Cadmus Labs is underground of the memorial and is taking the casket of superman of course this will be Superboy.

description:
While Luthor continues to pursue Superman's body, Jonathan Kent arrives at the hospital. Will Pa survive, or will he join his son in the afterlife?

The Kents were the first to find the infant Kal-El when he arrived on Earth. They took him in and raised him as their own. This issue explores a father's grief. It's never easy when a parent outlives their child. It gets even worse when this grief causes Jonathan Kent to have a heart attack. Plus, Lex Luthor's epitaph to his fallen enemy.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe" one page text piece featuring "R.I.P. Superman" what's new for 1993 to include Vertigo leaving DC, "New Stars on the Horizon" featuring the debut of Darkstars in their own title, "How to Draw Lobo" and "DC Bullets" Lee Moder makes his debut in Wonder Woman #72, Scott Peterson and Bill Kaplan are DC's newest editors, Tim Truman and John Ostrander team up for the last issue of Hawkworld #32 and Kevin Dooley paid $10 and a ham sandwich to get his name in this issue of DC Universe.
  • Series goes on a two month hiatus till June 1993.
  • Triangle 1993 #10.
  • Chronological continuation from Action Comics #686.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #500.

description:
Reign of the Supermen! "Alive!" Guest-starring the Guardian. Can it be true...has the Man of Steel returned from the grave? Someone, or something, has arrived with the look and power of the fallen hero, and he's here for Doomsday. Woe to any that would stand in his way. Includes a poster titled "The Man of Tomorrow!"

Notes:

  • The newstand edition was $1.50.
  • The direct sales edition was $1.95.
  • The direct sales cover is die-cut.
  • There is an outline of the "S" shield is on the outer cover while the "S" shield belongs to Cyborg Superman on the inner cover.
  • The direct sales and newstand covers were penciled by Dan Jurgens, inked by Brett Breeding and colored by Glenn Whitmore.
  • Story continues from Adventures of Superman #500.
  • "The Man of Tommorrow!" a poster of Cyborg Superman by Dan Jurgens and Brett Breeding.
  • Series returns after a two month hiatus.
  • Triangle 1993 #14.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #22.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #501.

description:
Reign of the Supermen tie-in.

Four men of power have arrived, seemingly out of nowhere, and all claim to be the Man of Steel incarnate. Daily Planet reporter Ronald Troupe writes an expose exploring the facts and mystery behind the return of Superman, or Supermen, as the case maybe.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe 10" one page text piece featuring "Larger Than Life: The Atom!", "The Man is Back! or is He?" and "DC Bullets" featuring a Lobo movie?, Stuart Immonen is a father, Phil Jimenez speaks at his old alma mater the School of Visual Arts to speak to the students and Dan Jurgens is a father. The Atom artwork by Steve Dillon, Superman(?) artwork by Jon Bogdanove and Dennis Janke and Conner Jones Immonen by Ron Boyd.
  • Triangle 1993 #18.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #23.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #502.

description:
Reign of the Supermen! "Deadly Alliance!" The Cyborg-Superman and the Kryptonian make war for the right to be the one true Superman, and Coast City is caught in the middle. Plus, Lex Luthor is beside himself. With his greatest enemy lying in his final resting place, the nefarious villain must now contend with four doppelgangers who all claim the mantle of Superman. Plus, a shocking final page you just can't miss.

Notes:

  • Cameo headshots of Steel and Superboy.
  • This is a dark chapter in the history of the DC Universe. One that leads to the fall from grace of one hero (Hal Jordan). Destruction of Coast City (leads to Green Lantern's Emerald Twilight).
  • Triangle 1993 #22.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #24.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #503.

description:
Reign of the Supermen! "Resurrections!" Guest-starring Supergirl, Superboy and Steel. The one true Man of Steel has returned! Now, Superman, along with the new Superboy and the man called Steel, must prepare themselves for the final battle with the treacherous Cyborg-Superman and his sinister accomplice, Mongul.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe 12" one page text piece featuring "Are You a Guy's Guy?" a Guy Gardner challenge with humorous questions and multiple choice answers. Plus, "How to Draw Robin" and "DC Bullets" which welcomes Peter Tomasi, Mike McAvennie and Keri Kowalski to the DC family, match the editor to their assistant editor and the creation of a new studio in North Carolina by Mike Wieringo, Richard Case, John Love and Chuck Wojtkiewicz. Guy Gardner artwork by Joe Staton and Terry Beatty and Robin artwork by Tom Grummett and Scott Hanna.
  • Triangle 1993 #26.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #25.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #504.

description:
This is it--Superman vs. Cyborg Superman! Even with help from Superboy, Steel, Supergirl, and the returning Eradicator, does Superman have a chance to win a battle against an enemy so powerful?!

Part of the Reign of the Supermen storyline. Its Mongul and the Cyborg Superman against Superman, Superboy, Supergirl, Steel, the Eradicator, and Hal Jordan in what remains of Coast City.

Notes:

  • Newstand and direct sales edition priced at $2.00.
  • Foil cover edition priced at $3.50.
  • Foil cover edition contains no ads.
  • Foil cover edition contains the creator's data.
  • Newstand and direct sales edition the creator's data is missing.
  • "DC Universe 13" one page featuring a Zero Hour teaser.
  • Read Green Lantern #46 prior to reading this issue.
  • Triangle 1993 #30.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #26.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #505.
name: Back For Good!

description:
Guest-starring Batman (Azrael) & the Justice League. Superman is back! As the Man of Steel makes his rounds to announce his return, he soon learns the DC Universe is a much different place than the one he left a few months ago. First stop...Gotham City, where a new person wears the mantle of the Bat.

Notes:

  • At this time in DC history Azrael took over as Batman for Bruce Wayne, who was nursing a broken back - courtesy of the hulking villain Bane.
  • Engine City is destroyed.
  • "DC Universe 13" one page featuring a Zero Hour teaser.
  • Triangle 1993 #34.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #27.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #506.

description:
The Toyman is back and more dangerous than ever. And this time the diabolical villain will use the son of Cat Grant as a pawn in his deadly game.

"Toys" Part 1 of 2. The Toyman is back and more dangerous than ever. And this time the diabolical villain will use the son of Cat Grant as a pawn in his deadly game. Nothing will prepare you for the tragic ending in this one.

Notes:

  • Jimmy Olsen was dressed up as Turtle Boy for Halloween.
  • Triangle 1993 #38.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #28.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #507.

description:
"The Last Sun Devil" While lost in space, thanks to Lobo (see Superman: The Man of Steel #30), Superman gets caught in the middle of two warring factions. Can the Man of Steel determine who is the good guy and who is the bad guy in this alien dispute before it's too late?

Notes:

  • Triangle 1994 #6.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #30.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #509.

description:
Bizarro's World! Part 1 of 5. "Bizarro!" Back in Man of Steel #5 Lex Luthor created a clone of the Man of Steel. This Frankenstein-like creature transformed into a disfigured parody of the original and became Bizarro, one of Superman's most dangerous enemies. Soon after its creation the Bizarro creature was destroyed but not before causing all sorts of chaos and destruction. You'd think that Luthor would have learned his lesson from this previous failure. Don't bet on it.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1994 #10.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #31.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #510.

description:
The Man of Steel finds himself helpless and uncontrollably growing in outer space. What has caused his sudden mutation, and can he be cured before it's too late?

"Desperation!" Part 4 of 5. The Man of Steel finds himself helpless and uncontrollably growing in outer space. What has caused his sudden mutation, and can he be cured before it's too late? Meanwhile, Lex Luthor makes things uncomfortable for Lois Lane at the Daily Planet.

Notes:

  • Lois Lane is fired from the Daily Planet.
  • "DC Universe" a one page text piece honoring the memory of Jack Kirby.
  • Triangle 1994 #18.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #33.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #512.

description:
The Battle for Metropolis! Part 3 of 4. "Battle Ground Metropolis" Guest-starring the Guardian. The Guardian has fallen victim to the clone disease, but does his body hold the key to the cure? Plus, a villain dies in this issue and the war heats up even more.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe 17" "From the DC High 1994 Yearbook" one page featuring Damage by Bill Marimon and Tom McWeeney, the Ray by Joe Quesada, Anima by Steve Crespo and Chris Ivy, Superboy by Tom Grummett and Doug Hazlewood, Robin by Tom Grummett and Scott Hanna and a good luck note from "Principal Carlin". Each character featured: Voted, Afterschool Activities, Quote and Immediate Plans.
  • Triangle 1994 #22.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #34.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #513.

description:
Fall of Metropolis! Part 3 of 5. "My Life!" Lex Luthor is dying and if Luthor can't have Metropolis than he'll see to it that there is no Metropolis! The diabolical villain enacts his endgame plan and unleashes an army of extermination robots on the city he's already crippled.

Notes:

  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #35.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #514.

description:
Massacre in Metropolis! "Earth Run!" Part 1 of 2. Superman must battle a foe whose strength rivals his own. It's the Man of Steel versus the powerhouse known as Massacre for the fate of the world.

Notes:

  • Adam Grant cameo headshot appearance.
  • A one paragraph dedicated to memory of T. M. Maple who recently passed away. T. M. Maple was an avid letter writer to the various comic book companies from the 1970s to the 1980s.
  • "DC Universe 18" one page advertisement piece with information on the upcoming Chicago Comicon 1994. Included are dates, times and location of the convention plus the creators who will be on hand at the show.
  • Triangle 1994 #30.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #36.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #515.

description:
"Revenge of Apokolips!" When a Para-Demon from Apokolips arrives in Metropolis, Superman is shocked to learn it's not here to fight. Instead, the former servant of Darkseid has come seeking the Man of Steel's help. Superman faces off with the Lord of Apokolips, plus the return of the Cyborg-Superman.

Notes:

  • Triangle 1995 #35.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #48.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #527.

description: The Trial of Superman! Part 2 of 12. "Misperceptions!" Story continued from Superman: The Man of Steel #50. When the galactic judicial committee known as the Tribunal abducts the Man of Steel and charges him with being responsible for the destruction of Krypton, Superman has a tough decision to make. Use his great powers to escape this bogus wrap, or stay and face the music, and somehow clear his good name. Story continues in Adventures of Superman (1939-2006) #529.

description:
Lori Lemaris-Clark Kent's college love whom he thought was dead, and who just so happens to be a mermaid-is back. And, Superman and Lois Lane's relationship falls on turbulent times.

After the breakup with Lois, Kent begins to question her motives and becomes angry with having to oblige to his duties as a hero which conflict with his time spent with Lois. Superman and Lori Lemaris work together to retrieve Jeb's dead body that fell in the sea, using Lori's knowledge of the sea and Superman's vision they stumble upon the body already picked at by sharks. Kent reveals his situation with Lois to Lori and expresses his frustration at not being able to have a normal life. Kent then becomes determined to get Lois back.
name: Divisions

description:
Professor Thaddeus Killgrave attempts to escape from prison, leaving the Man of Steel with an impossible choice…save the prison guards and star reporter Lois Lane from a rampaging robot, or recapture the fleeing villain. Plus, Superman and Lois Lane break up!

As Superman battles a prison break on Strikers Island, Morgan Edge escapes. Meanwhile, Lois Lane tries to have a conversation with Superman regarding their relationship, they are interrupted by a call for Superman's help. She urges him to go, although it appears she would rather him stay but she doesn't want to be selfish. This seemingly marks the end of Lois and Clark's relationship.
name: Superman's Ex-Girlfriend Lois Lane

description:
"A Hard Days Night!" Guest-starring Booster Gold. Booster and Superman together again! But things sure have changed for the two heroes since the last time they teamed up. Can this odd couple with a turbulent history help each other get back on track? Plus, Scorn makes a startling discovery.

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage of the cover of Action Comics #1.

description:
Luthor and the Contessa have become proud parents! And when Lex promises his bouncing baby that "someday, all this will be yours," he's referring to Metropolis! What sinister plan does Lex have in mind to guarantee that the newest Luthor will be his successor?

Superman with his new energy-based powers wearing a containment suit is out of Metropolis to deal with some military issue somewhere far away.

Lex Luthor is remembering the time as he was a kid in a foster family. Lex shows that he had a particular bond to the girl whose name, Lena.

Luthor's attending a speech in town, a story covered by the famous reporter of the Daily Planet, Lois Lane. Meanwhile, the child of the Contessa Erica Alexandra Del Portenza is about to be given birth.

Indeed, Lex Luthor has something in mind. During the speech, the speaker is suddenly shot and at the meantime, Superman, is saving the world and the awaiting child is born.

Lex Luthor pulled the strings to get the revenge of the murder of the only girl he'd ever loved, Lena by setting up her murderer, their foster father, Casey Griggs. He was paid for killing the speaker and as Superman is not in Metropolis, the crime could not have been prevented.

After dealing with the case, Luthor came to see Doctor Cordova and take his child in his arms, Lena Luthor. After Lena's birth, Lex takes advantage of Contessa Erica's wish to be unconscious at child birth by keeping her permanently drugged and unconscious at his corporate headquarters, not wishing to share his daughter's love with anyone else.
name: Checkmate

description:
Special Extra-Sized 150th issue. Earth's Final Hour!" With a title like "Earth's Final Hour" it can only mean one thing - Brainiac is back and he's deadlier than ever! And as if that weren't bad enough, Vartox, Vestion, and Paz (1st seen in Superman #148) arrive on Earth and they aren't on the side of angels.

Notes:

  • The Regular cover is a homage of the cover of Superman #14.
  • The Regular cover is penciled by Dan Jurgens and inked by Kevin Nowlan.
  • The Deluxe cover is pencled by Dan Jurgens and inked by Joe Rubinstein.
  • Last issue featuring writer Dan Jurgens.
  • Triangle 1999 #44.

description:
Aquaman makes a cameo in an exciting issue, featuring a striking cover by Dwayne Turner (Curse of the Spawn) and Danny Miki, who provide all of this month's Superman-ongoing titles' covers!

All his life Superman has kept himself in check, never unleashing his full power for fear of killing someone. Now the son of Mongul is asking him to unleash his full potential in order to save Earth, but in doing so will the Man of Steel lose himself? Plus, Jimmy shoots the scoop of the century, which has everyone asking, "Who is Mrs. Superman?"

"1999 1"--Triangle in upper left hand corner.
name: The Fury of Superman!; Deadline U.S.A.

description:
Done with his lethal training at the side of young Mongul, Superman and the junior villain head into the depths of space to confront Imperiex. This enigmatic being is powerful enough to live in a black hole and all too ready to turn the Earth into one! Will Superman's new battle skills be enough to stop Imperiex? And can the Man of Steel trust his new ally?

Imperex appearing for the first time.

description:
Part 1 of "Return to Krypton," the storyline running through all the Superman books in February. Taking Lois with him, Superman returns to the land of his birth - but now it's seen in a way it hasn't looked in almost twenty years. Can Superman save this Silver Age Krypton from its destruction?

To be continued in Adventures of Superman 589

description:
Lois seeks out Batman, the one person who can retrieve President Luthor's Kryptonite ring. But Lois and the Dark Knight have an obstacle in their way--the Man of Steel!

The Kents and Lanes have a rousing dinner together; Perry reveals that Bruce Wayne has been the secret backer for the Daily Planet; Lois and Bats begin their attempt to steal the Kryptonite Ring from President Luthor.

The alien Korsa Majalis journeys to Earth to enlist Superman's aid, after Korsa's planet is corrupted and turned into energy by the sentient space virus Viroxx. But is Superman enough to halt the course of this seemingly unstoppable cosmic disease?

description:
Mongul is back to settle the score with Superman and he's not alone. He's brought his lovely sister, Mongal, to share in the kill. But the Man of Steel is not without his own backup, and Krypto's bite is far worse than his bark!

Clark Kent and Lois Lane have taken Krypto for a stroll to the park. Then Superman's old enemy Mongul comes down. Krypto attacks at once, with Superman joining in, shortly afterwards. But more surprise awaits Superman.

Mongul has brought with him his sister, Mongal. Together they give Superman a tough fight. But Superman is able to shake off both of them. Mongal escapes, leaving Mongul behind to be taken into custody.

Superman thinks it will be safe to leave Krypto at the Fortress of Solitude and acts likewise.

description:
Part 1 The vanished planet Pluto reemerges and Superman must investigate, but he soon finds himself battling a deadly time-displaced Fatal Five. Meanwhile, President Luthor has a close encounter with an alien woman who brings portents of destruction. Will the President listen or will it be a day that will live in infamy?

Superman, (with Hamilton on a com unit) checks out the planet that appeared where the missing Pluto once was. He soon discovers that it is in fact a new Warworld. Before he can investigate farther, he is attacked by the Fatal Five. Superman soon realizes that the Fatal Five are only holograms and defeats them. He then flies into the center of the new Warworld where he learns that Brainiac is behind the deception. Before he can learn more Brainiac blows up the new Warworld forcing Superman to wonder while he was in space, what did he miss happen on Earth.

Meanwhile, while Superman was in space, President Luthor is visited by his daughter, who Brainiac aged into an adult. She tells him there is a war coming and if he wants Earth to survive, he will need to listen to her and make some scarifies. Luthor agrees but has his own plans in mind.

Notes-This issue has references to Superman #159 the disappearance of Pluto, Action Comics #770 Lex Luthor giving his daughter to Brainiac, and Superman #170 the destruction of Warworld.
name: Of Course, You Know, This Means...Warworld!

description:
As Clark Kent and Lois Lane move into their new apartment, Clark reminisces about his times in Smallville. In particular, his memories turn to Kenny Braverman, a friend who always came in second behind Clark. Little does Clark know that Kenny has now become the super-villain Conduit, and is gunning for Clark. Clark has won a Baldy Award, and Conduit has set up a bomb at the awards ceremony. Luckily, Superman has come in to save the day, rescuing everyone at the awards. Superman defeats Conduit’s agents that continue the assault, but does not discover who is behind the attempt on Clark’s life. When Clark returns to his apartment, he finds his photo with a knife through it attached to his door. Now, Clark is sure someone is gunning for him as Clark Kent, not Superman.

Notes:

  • On page 5 panel 2 Clark Kent has a Captain Action action figure.
  • A Zero Hour crossover issue.
  • Triangle 1994 #38.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #0.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #0.
name: Peer Pressure Part 2: Awards

description: Kal Kent, Superman from the 853rd Century saves Roy Harper from Vandal Savage's Rocket Red suit, which had been set on auto pilot to detonate in Metropolis, and programmed to defend it self from any opposition. A mob, driven mad by the Hourman Virus, mistrusts and attacks him, but Roy and the local authorities hold them off while Kal meets up with Lois Lane and they search for components to build a solar computer to contain the virus. Lex Luthor offers assistance but ultimately betrays them, as he too is affected by the Hourman Virus. Even though Kal's powers are fading one by one in the absence of the Super Sun of his era, he defeats Luthor's armored guards and escapes with Lois. Having failed to find the parts he needs and unable to enter the Fortress of Solitude, he resolves to go to the JLA Watchtower on the Moon.

description:
A 48-page extravaganza featuring the final battle between Superman and the Futuresmiths! The shocking revelation of who they really are, the final fate of Metropolis, and a look at possible future origins of Batman, Wonder Woman, and Superman. Plus, an appearance by Supergirl and a shocking ending you won't want to miss! Also featuring a tour of Metropolis featuring designs by Lee Bermejo (BATMAN/DEATHBLOW: AFTER THE FIRE) and Leinil Yu (SUPERMAN: BIRTHRIGHT).

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage of the cover of Superman #233.
name: The Last Superman Story

description:
The 3-part "Strange New Visitor" reaches a stunning conclusion, as Superman is still missing! Believing that Majestic is the cause of the crisis that is plaguing Metropolis, the heroes unite against him. But will this lead to a greater cataclysm for the city? And what happens when a hero falls?

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage of the cover of Action Comics #1.

description:
Overview

In issue #206, Big Blue came face-to-face with a seemingly unstoppable foe backed by a ruthless dictator. While Superman has vowed not to take sides in a civil unrest, he finally must decide on whether he maintains his neutrality or takes up arms. However, will he choose the right side to defend? Can he trust those he's sworn to defend. Stay tuned, because an unstoppable monster and oppressive regime aren't the only dilemmas Superman has to contend with in this issue!

description: Overview Pushed to his mental limits, Superman decides to destroy the cause of the mysterious vanishings in front of the world. But how will the people of Earth react to this seemingly benevolent action? Meanwhile, Father Leone makes a confession of his own that will turn this story upside down. Don’t miss what’s sure to be one of the most talked-about Superman stories in years!
name: For Tomorrow, Part Six

description:
It’s the battle between the DCU’s strongest heroes: Superman vs. Wonder Woman in a fight to the finish, written by fan-favorite Brian Azzarello and illustrated by Jim Lee & Scott Wiliams as “For Tomorrow” continues!

When Superman inadvertently sets off a series of catastrophic events after destroying the Vanishing Tech, Wonder Woman must intervene and attempt to put an end to the chaos. But Superman has plans of his own and won’t let the Amazonian interfere without a fight — and what a fight it’ll be!
name: For Tomorrow, Part Seven
