description: "For Tomorrow" Part 8 of 12 ? the epic Azzarello, Lee & Williams run continues! Still reeling from his brutal encounter with Wonder Woman, Superman realizes that the deadly assassin Mr. Orr has been using the Man of Steel's clouded judgment all along. Will Superman be able to counter Orr's evil deeds? And what does a wicked new villainess have in store for Big Blue?
name: For Tomorrow, Part Eight

description: Superman has brought himself to the world of the Vanished.  He meets Clark Kent there and realizes that he should trust him once again with a secret.  He then goes and embraces Lois, as the two share a moment that only lovers can.  Clark Kent, meanwhile is ambushed and brutally beaten by a creature that answers to a man known only as the General.

description: "For Tomorrow" part 10 of 12, the Man of Steel moves closer to solving the mystery that has been plaguing him! After becoming a victim of the Vanishings, Superman now comes face-to-face with the person ? or persons ? responsible for the disappearances of millions of Earth's citizens. Who's powerful enough to pull off this act? Superman's about to find out!

description:
An INFINITE CRISIS tie-in! With the full weight of the Crisis events on his shoulders, the Man of Steel undergoes a drastic change as he wages an all-out war in Metropolis!

In an Infinite Crisis Crossover, Superman is found on the roof the the Daily Planet pondering Batman's latest statements to him. Lois arrives and informs him its time to head down. Jimmy has headed west, While John Henry Irons looks at photo's of the OMAC's. Superman is able to save some people from a sticky situation as Conner Kent continues to look on, fearing that coming out as Superboy will put a damper on the heroics of Superman.
name: To Be a Hero

description:
Bizarro's World! Part 5 of 5. "Opportunity Lost". Bizarro is at the mercy of Luthor's scientists and only Superman and Lois can save him now. Or can they?

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage to the cover of The X-Men #100.
  • A letter to the editor from the Polly Klaas Foundation concerning the killing of Adam Grant in Superman #84.
  • "DC Universe 16" "What is TV Like in the DC Universe?" one page text piece taking a humorous look at a page from a TV channel guide. Artwork by ??? Banks and Romeo Tanghal.
  • Triangle 1994 #14.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #32.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #511.

description:
The question has been raised—is Superman the genuine article returned from the dead, or is he simply another imposter? Seeking answers, the Man of Steel, New Gods and the Atom seek out the one being who has messed with Superman's head more than anyone—Brainiac!

After ruling out the Eradicator and Luthor, Superman’s next suspect for the creation of a duplicate corpse of himself is Brainiac. Superman enlists Emil Hamilton’s aid in repairing his defunct Mother Box. Hamilton does the job, and Superman is Boom Tubed to New Genesis; however, Superman has a hitch-hiker: the Atom. The Atom has been de-aged to a teenager after the events of Zero Hour, and is hoping to use Metron’s knowledge to return him to his rightful age. When the two arrive in Metron’s lab, Atom infiltrates Metron’s Mobius Chair. However, Atom does not have the knowledge he once did, and accidentally teleports the chair, and the room, into space nearby a black hole. Metron eventually repairs the damage, and Atom stays on New Genesis. Superman discovers that Brainiac is comatose. With Brainiac ruled out, Superman’s next suspect is Darkseid, and he prepares for a visit to Apokolips.

Notes:

  • Cameo flashback appears of of Milton Fine and Vril Dox as Brainiac.
  • Cameo flashback headshot of Superman disguised as Gangbuster.
  • Cameo appearances of Darkseid, Cyborg-Superman and Apokolips.
  • "DC Universe 23" one page advertisement piece made to look like the front page of the Daily Planet with information on Deathstroke.
  • Curtis King credited as the cover editor.
  • Triangle 1994 #46.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #39.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #518.

description:
What's Santa got in his bag for Superman this year? A brand-new Toyman, made in Japan, that's who. And he's looking to add Metallo to his collection of giant robots!

It's Christmas time in Metropolis, and Superman has plenty of fan mail to answer. However, in the middle of the city, there is a battle going on! New Toyman is pummeling Metallo with hundreds of tiny electronic Superman figures, claiming that the parts that built Metallo rightfully belong to him, the Toyman.

Superman dispatches them easily, and returns to the Daily Planet as Clark Kent, where he finds one more piece of mail. It turns out to be one last holiday wish, this one from Lois. She is in Egypt, and she misses him. Then, the story ends with a shocking discovery--Lex Luthor knew that Lois' father was going to die--before it happened!!
name: Metropolis E-Mailbag

description:
"Dead Again!" Part 2 of 11. Superman battles Conduit in an epic struggle of life and death. But how can the Man of Steel prevail against an adversary whose primary weapon is Kryptonite?

Conduit’s victory from Superman: The Man of Steel #38 is premature, as Superman recovers and reengages Conduit high above Metropolis. The two of them give and take during the battle. Conduit tries to entangle Superman in his Kryptonite-powered tendrils, but Superman escapes. Superman goes underground, ambushing Conduit, and melting molten lead on his armor. The lead helps prevent the Kryptonite radiation from affecting Superman, giving him the upper hand. Conduit distracts Superman, as he leaves to kill Clark Kent. Instead of finding Clark in Kent’s apartment, he finds his own father. His father convinces him to surrender. Meanwhile, Emil Hamilton has confirmed that the duplicate of Superman discovered in Centennial Park is the real Superman.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe 22" "Comics Coloring Demystified" one page text piece describing a six steps processing that goes into coloring a comic book. Artwork by Tom Grummett and Scott Hanna.
  • Triangle 1994 #42.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #38.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #517.
name: Shadows of the Past

description:
The House of Dracula. Can the Man of Steel defeat the Lord of the Night?

Clark Kent, Lois Lane and Jimmy Olsen are sent "somewhere in Eastern Europe" to get a interview with Count Rominoff. A chain of bizzare and inexplicable events take place, with Lois losing control of herself. Superman comes to save her and comes face to face with Dracula. At the end it is revealed that Rominoff is really Dracula, and wants to turn Superman into a vampire to lead his army, against the evil General Zod. He attempts to take control of Superman's mind but bungles everything when he goes to draw Superman's blood. The pure energy contained in it incinerates Dracula and with it, his plans for Superman.
name: The House of Dracula

description:
One fine morning, Superman and Bizzaro wake up in each others bodies. Confusion ensues, with Clark Kent(Bizzaro) breaking out of his apartment much to Lois' surprise. Elsewhere, Bizzaro(Superman) flies up from the Graveyard of Solitude and breaks into the Justice League's base on the Moon.He gets attacked by his teammates, who don't recognize him. Jo'nn Jo'nnz helps him out. 
Superman returns to Earth, only to find Bizzaro making a ruckus inside The Daily Planet. A fight ensues, with Superman confronting General Zod inside Bizzaro's dreams. They both return to their own bodies. 
The Martian Manhunter appears as Superman and has a quick conversation with Clark. 
At the end, it is revealed that Manchester Black is the mastermind beind all the bizzare events taking place that day.
name: THE MIRROR CRACK'D

description:
Extra-sized issue! Exactly one hundred issues ago, the impossible happened: Superman died. Now his killer has returned, deadlier than ever! Make way for the all-new Doomsday Rex! This "Last Laugh" tie-in will slay you!

"2001 46" in Superman "S" in upper right hand corner

Joker breaks into the Pentagon and uses his joker venom on Doomsday who is being kept in stasis. Doomsday attacks while Lex Luthor is giving a speech at the White House. Superman and Doomsday fight one the White House lawn and eventually move the battle to inside the White House itself. Lex Luthor springs a trap which captures Superman and Doomsday and admits synthetic kryptonite radiation. The radiation, having more of an effect on Superman than Doomsday allows the latter to gain the upper-hand and then break out of the trap. Martian Manhunter who had been disguised within the White House confronts Doomsday and enters his mind. Doomsday beats Martian Manhunter. Superman, having had time to recover, slams into Doomsday knocking him into the Lincoln Memorial. Martian Manhunter warns that Doomsday is learning and understanding what is going on around him. Superman races to the Lincoln Memorial and begins fighting with Doomsday. Throughout the course of the fight Superman explains that since Doomsday is now sentient he is becoming aware of pain, doubt, and he understands that he doesn't want to die today. Superman knocks Doomsday unconscious and is then approached by Luthor letting him know the Department of Extranormal Operations will handle taking Doomsday back into confinement. We cut to Lex Luthor meeting with Darkseid, Luthor reveals he let loose Doomsday as a sort of weapons test to prove Doomsday's worth to Darkseid. The issue ends with Superman returning home to visit his parents who were worried about him during his fight with Doomsday.
name: Joker: Last Laugh: Doomsday Rex

description:
Superman recruits Supergirl’s help in combating the time rifts discovered during Zero Hour. While heading back to New York City to regroup with the rest of the heroes, Superman stops by Smallville to check up on his parents. However, he is shocked to find Jor-El and Lara standing there. Evidently, the time fluctuations have caused an alternate-reality Jor-El and Lara to appear; a couple from a timeline where Krypton did not explode after they sent Kal-El to Earth. In this continuity, Kal-El has a brother Zan-El. While Jor-El and Lara want Superman to return to them on Krypton, Superman realizes that this is just another time anomaly. He does get to spend one last moment with them before they fade, just before Metron arrives to urge Superman to meet up with the rest of the heroes.

Notes:

  • "DC Universe 19" one page advertisement piece with information on the upcoming Zero Hero mini-series. Plus, San Diego Comic-Con 1994. Included are dates, times and location of the convention.
  • A Zero Hour crossover issue.
  • Triangle 1994 #34.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #37.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #516.

description:
Get ready for one of the most off-beat adventures of the Last Son Krypton. In a virtual world of the mind, Superman seeks the truth to the mystery of whether or not he is the real deal. Featuring appearances by Batman, Lois Lane, the Silver Banshee, Guardian, Superboy, the Kryptonian, Steel, Cyborg-Superman, Ma & Pa Kent and Doomsday!

The culprit behind the Dead Again! story arc is revealed to be Brainiac. While the people of Metropolis look on confused, Superman is bombarded with illusion after illusion by Brainiac. While Superman encounters Ma and Pa Kent, Batman, his replacements from Reign of the Supermen, a fake sidekick named Skyboy and Doomsday all in his mind, the residents of the city watch him flail about, destroying parts of the city. The Metropolis S.C.U. tries to protect as many as they can, while Guardian watches over Superman. Emil Hamilton comes on the scene with a neural neutralizer gun, which, after fired at Superman, forces Superman’s mind to break through the illusions. Once Superman is free, he realizes that Guardian is actually Brainiac in disguise. Superman finally gets to confront Brainiac directly.

Notes:

  • Except for Superman, Lois Lane, Maggie Sawyer, Emil Hamilton and Brainiac all other characters appear as hallucinations.
  • "DC Universe 25" "What Exactly Does an Inker Do?"a one page text piece with four panels of the same artwork. The first panel is the penciller's work the next three panels are inked by three different inkers to show the different styles of ink work on the artwork. The artwork was penciled by Jim Balent and inked by Scott Hanna, Gerry Fernandez and Jed Hotchkiss. The artwork was from Detective Comics #660.
  • Curtis King credited as the cover editor.
  • Triangle 1995 #2.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #40.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #519.

description: In an OMAC Project Tie-in Lois Lane is attacked by an OMAC. She has entered her panic room, but to no avail as the OMAC is able to find her, Lois picks up a weapon left to her by Superman. Meanwhile a flashback shows Clark undermining an investigation by Lois 24 hours earlier. As the day wears on, and Lois begins to lose ground on the OMAC, the question remains where is Superman? Will he save the day?

  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #520.

"Changes!" Find out how the deranged Toyman made the jump from notoriously silly villain to child killer. The facts will shock Superman and Cat Grant, mother of the child Toyman murdered.

  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #42.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #521.

description:
"Burning the Past!" Legendary artist Gil Kane lends his unique talents to this issue. It's an issue that finds Superman side-by-side with Agent Liberty fighting against a fiery foe that could prove to be the end of them both.

Notes:

  • Larry Prince is a parody of Larry King.
  • Last $1.50 issue.
  • Last paper and color format used. The next issue uses heavier stock paper and glossy pages.
  • Triangle 1995 #14.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #43.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #522.

description:
Conduit has taken everything away from the Man of Steel. He's taken his family, his love, his city and his mission. Now he wants to take Superman's life. But, like anyone who is backed into a corner, the Last Son of Krypton is about to show his adversary why he is the greatest superhero of them all.

Grief...

In the previous issue, Conduit a.k.a. Kenny Braverman had tried every possible means to bring out Superman out of Clark Kent, even destroyed the Kent Farmhouse. He had almost succeeded, in the end Superman himself saying that "for all intents and purposes, Clark Kent and the entire Kent family are dead from this day on!"

But the threat to Kal-El's loved ones isn't over. Still, Superman is determined to turn the tide of battle back to Conduit!

Notes:

  • Clark Kent used the name Wayne Jordan when he applied for a job. Wayne was from Bruce Wayne and Jordan from Hal Jordan.
  • First $1.95 issue.
  • New paper and color format introduced. The issue is heavier and the pages glossier.
  • Triangle 1995 #22.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #45.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #524.
name: Grief

Love Hurts. So soon after regaining control of his body from Brainiac, Superman's control is usurped once more by a mysterious golden haired woman. Plus, Lois Lane leaves Metropolis behind. After that heartbreaking news there's really not much else to say, now is there.

"1996 33"--Triangle in upper left hand corner.

description:
Final Night. "Sanctuary!" As Superman and Professor Hamilton return to the Fortress of Solitude to try and help the Bottle City of Kandor, but they soon run into trouble. description:
"From the Heart!" Guest-starring Wonder Woman. In the aftermath of the Sun-Eaters attack (see Final Night (1996) #1-4), Superman remains powerless. As S.T.A.R. Labs tries to find a way to return his powers, Clark gets some much needed relationship advise from his close friend, Wonder Woman. Meanwhile, the woman in question, Lois Lane continues her adventures abroad.

"1996 46"--Triangle in upper left hand corner.

description:
"Trading Places!" Guest-starring Captain Marvel. The Cyborg-Superman is back and the Man of Steel intends to end his evil ways here and now. Plus, when the World's Mightiest Mortal spots his arch foe Black Adam he pounces. But, what these two heroes don't realize is that they're really fighting each other. Can someone please find out what is going on before the Earth's two strongest champions kill each other? Meanwhile, Lois continues her search for Clark.

Notes:

  • Black Adam and Cyborg Superman appeared as hallucinations.
  • Triangle 1995 #26.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #46.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #525.

description:
What caused the rebellious young prince of Kandor to phase out of the bottle city? What kind of trouble can befall an entire city whose population is comprised of oddly gifted aliens? Plus, Lois visits the Fortress of Solitude for the first time!

"It Begins Here! A New Life for Superman. What Lurks Within the Spires of Kandor? What New Menace Stalks Metropolis? What Threatens This Strange New World?"

description:
"It Takes More Than One Superman-- --To Save the Earth!"

The Millennium Giant! Epilogue. "Shattered Worlds!" Guest-starring the JLA, Teen Titans, and Steel. The Millennium Giants and the Millennium Guard have been defeated. So how come things are getting worse? Well Superman-Blue and Superman-Red better find out quick or this will be the shortest victory celebration in history! Starring Superman Red and Superman Blue, guest starring the JLA and the Teen Titans.

Millennium Giants cross-over issue

Continued from: Superman: The Man of Steel #79

Continues in: Superman: Forever #1

"1998 20"--Triangle in upper left hand corner.

description:
Superman Forever! Part 7. "Superman 2999!" Superman stands for Truth, Justice, and the American Way! He's the greatest hero in the DCU...the only problem is he's in the year 2999. Don't worry, it'll all make sense, in time.

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage of the cover of Action Comics #1.
  • Triangle 1998 #25.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #80.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #559.

description:
Meet the one villain that no Superman from any time period—Golden Age, Silver Age, Modern Age and beyond—may be able to defeat.

"Meet the Master of Reality... Dominus!"

The four Supermen on the cover are Supermen from different time periods.

Story continues in: Adventures of Superman #561

"1998 33"--Triangle in upper right hand corner.

Synopsis

The Superman's descendant in 2999 together with other heroes like Aquaman 2999, Batman 2999, Big Barda 2999, Flash 2999, Green Arrow 2999, Green Lantern 2999, Hawkman 2999, Martian Manhunter 2999, Robin 2999, Supergirl 2999, and Wonder Woman 2999 officially announce the formation of a superhero team called the Justice Alliance when a white-haired girl, appears to Superman to warn him about the reality he is in and the danger that he will face. Suddenly a camera flash causes him to see in a moment all four realities he was cast in: the 1960s, the 1970s, the 1940s that ended up becoming the present day, and the 2999 reality. In all four realities, the little girl became the female cosmic entity called Kismet who said that these realities were created in order to destroy Superman. However, the creator of these realities, Dominus, says these were created to find and destroy Kismet, and soon all four realities vanish as the Supermen of these realities merge together back into the single present-day Superman. As Superman and Kismet vanish to another part of the universe to talk about the problem they will confront, when suddenly Dominus appears to attack Kismet to the point of weakening her into a ball of energy and Superman unable to save her.

Characters

There are versions of characters in the future that appear in this comic book, those are:

  • Aquaman (2999)
  • Batman (2999)
  • Big Barda (2999)
  • Flash (2999)
  • Green Arrow (2999)
  • Green Lantern (2999)
  • Hawkman (2999)
  • Lena Luthor (2999)
  • Martian Manhunter (2999)
  • Robin (2999)
  • Supergirl (2999)
  • Superman (2999)
  • Wonder Woman (2999)

  • Triangle 1999 #4.

description:
"Clark Kent No More!" Humorous cameos by Blue Beetle, Booster Gold, Elongated Man, and Captain Atom. Superman makes a big decision that could change his life forever. When an entire world needs saving, there's no room in his life for Clark Kent. Plus, Outburst makes the scene.

Continues in: Adventures of Superman #565

Superman: I've tried to help everyone all over the world ... and this is the thanks I get!

"1999 8"--Triangle in upper left hand corner.

description:
McGuinness comes onboard as new penciler as the Brainiac 13 saga (which began in SUPERMAN Y2K) continues! As Metropolis morphs into a futuristic city capable of containing the new Brainiac (represented in an extraordinary CGI creation), Superman must cope with all the threats that come with his revamped stomping grounds, including a brand-new Metallo that towers over the city. Even with the help of the Metal Men, the Last Son of Krypton is outgunned. Meanwhile, Luthor finds salvation in the form of his daughter. Plus, the most unexpected return of all!

Continued from: Superman Y2K #1

Continues in: Adventures of Superman #576

"For Truth. For Justice. Forever!"

"2000 10"--Superman "S" in upper left hand corner.
name: Whatever Happened to the City of Tomorrow?  :Y2K Two of 5

description:
Superboy guest stars in a tale of two cities, contrasting the new mega-city of Metropolis and the prototypically rural Smallville. After making sure that the transformed Metropolis is safe, Superman decides to head back to the homestead for a little R & R, and is surprised to find the Teen of Steel hanging around the family farm. Can Clark keep his secret identity hidden with the Kid around?

"Return to Smallville"

"2000 14"--Superman "S" in upper left hand corner.

After having trouble in the city, Clark decieds to visit Ma and Pa at the farm and have a relaxing time, but Superboy is at home and making himself comfortable.

description:
Team Superman and the Atom must make a fantastic voy...journey to save the Man of Steel in part 1 of the 4-part story, “Critical Condition”! Superman has collapsed and now it's up to the Atom and Team Superman (Superboy, Supergirl and Steel) to save him. And the only way to do that is to shrink and enter Superman's body!

It's a "Super" Fantastic Voyage into Superman. Can a shrunken Team Superman and Atom save Superman?

Continues in: Adventures of Superman #580

This story arc is reprinted in Superman: Critical Condition (2003)

"2000 26"--Superman "S" in upper left hand corner.

description:
Green Lantern guest-stars in a spacefaring issue! To make sure he's okay after last month's "Critical Condition," Superman enlists Green Lantern to help put him through his paces. But the checkup, conducted in the void of space (in sequences illustrated by former GL artist Paul Pelletier), the two soon find themselves fighting for their lives against Maxima and Massacre. And that's far from the worst threat our heroes are going to face.

"2000 30"--Superman "S" in upper left hand corner

A follow up to the "Critical Condition" storyline

description:
The Super-event of the Summer begins with Part 1 of the 4-part "Superman: Arkham!" Able to bend steel in his bare hands, leap tall buildings in a single bound, it's the black-clad, most wanted criminal to escape Arkham Asylum: Superman. Night after night he escapes his prison, only to be brought back as the sun comes up by Earth's Greatest Hero: Bizarro! And each night, like clockwork, a painful scream can be heard in the distance...

Superman escapes from prison and Bizarro is called in to put him back!!!

This issue is a "flip" cover with Superman and Bizarro on either side.

Story continues in: Adventures of Superman #582

"2000 34"--Superman "S" in upper left and lower right hand corner.
name: Superman Arkham Part 1: It's a Mad, Mad, Mad World !

description:
Superman is rebuilding the fortress of solitude in a small village in Perú, he went there and didn't tell Lois were he was going. He has been gone for three weeks and still no notice from were he is. Lois recieved some pictures that might dictate were he is, so she and Jimmy Olsen went there to find him.

Superman's presence atracted some people there, so they captured Lois and Jimmy in order to get his attention, after he saved them, he took them to the village and introduced them to the new fortress. The very next day the same people attacked the village, when Superman tried to save them he was attacked by an strange being capable of holding a fight with him. He couldn't saved them and the people lost faith in him, he felt bad afterwards.
name: The Journey

description:
Superman and Superboy find their way to the ruins of the old Fortress of Solitude in the Arctic with John Henry Irons to check on the missing Eradicator. Unfortunately, the Eradicator still believes Krypton's sons are rogues, and he's prepared to take care of that problem!

Superman and Superboy talk about what just happened recently to them, how they were controlled and forced to attack their friends. John Henry AKA as Steel was investigating the ruins of the destroyed Fortress of Solitude, when Eradicator who was trapped was released and was acting berserk. Superman and Superboy reach the place to stop him, when suddenly an OMAC appeared and stopped Eradicator in a single blow.

description:
"Ending Battle" Part 5 of 8! The hunt for the mastermind behind the stalking of Clark Kent's friends and family continues! Superman returns to a Metropolis turned into a prison by the new Master Jailer. But that's not all ? guarding the gates of that prison are deadlier versions of the Prankster, Bizarro, Metallo, and an all-new, female Puzzler.

Story continued from: Action Comics #795

Story continues in: Adventures of Superman #609

"Welcome to Penitentiary" (with the word Penitentiary written over the word Metropolis)
name: Ending Battle Part 5: After School Special

description:
A special issue focusing on Lois Lane, by guest-writer Chuck Austen (Ultimate X-Men) and guest-artists Pascal Alixe (LEGION LOST) & Ray Snyder. Lois reflects on her life with Superman. She's married to the most powerful man in the universe, so how does this affect her daily life? How does she cope with the possible death of her husband each and every day?

Also includes an 8 page preview of the new Aqauaman series written by Rick Veitch

description:
Part one of Lost Hearts. Continues in Adventures of Superman #611.

Overview

Part 1 of 4 begins, continuing throughout all the Superman books this month! Lana Lang answers a call for help from the slums of Washington D.C. and mysteriously disappears! Her husband, Vice President Pete Ross, calls Clark Kent to help. But this might not be a job for Superman, as he realizes there are darker forces at work. Featuring guest cameos by Batman and Power Girl!

description:
There are two versions of this comic. The normal version only contains the story "Justice". The "Extra Double Feature Issue" version contains the story "Truth", a prologue reprinted from "Superman: The 10 Cent Adventure". The same comic team worked on both stories, except Richard Starkings did not work on the story "Justice."

  1. "Truth" (Superman, Supergirl, Lois Lane, Perry White, Jimmy Olsen, Lex Luthor, Futuresmiths, Martha Kent and Johnathan Kent) written by Steven Seagle, penciled by Scott McDaniel, inked by Andy Owens, colored by Tanya and Richard Horie and lettered by Richard Starkings. This is a reprint of Superman 10-Cent Adventure
  2. "Justice" (Superman, Supergirl, Lex, FutureSmiths, Talia, Lois, Perry and Jimmy) written by Steven Seagle, penciled by Scott McDaniel, inked by Andy Owens, colored by Tanya and Richard Horie and lettered by .
name: Truth / Justice

description:
Part 1 of "This Is Your Life, Superman," a 3-part tale running through all three Superman titles in February! Witness the arrival of Kal-L, the Last Son of Krypton! Learn how he grew up to be the greatest hero of Earth-2. This issue includes a special origin album by Jeph Loeb & Tim Sale, the creative team behind SUPERMAN FOR ALL SEASONS! ?

Story continues in Action Comics #836.

description:
Superman is on the run from a villain who knows too much about him. In order to protect the ones closest to him, will the Man of Steel do the unthinkable?

Someone has kept a rag-doll of Superman inside Clark Kent's office drawer, means someone knows who Superman is. Superman knows the danger and goes over to his Kansas farmhouse, informing his parents about the details, and telling them that they all should leave at the earliest. Elsewhere Lana Lang and her husband Pete Ross receive a gift of a Champagne bottle from an anonymous sender.

In Metropolis, Conduit raids Clark's apartment, destroys it and takes Jimmy Olsen with him. He rings up Superman to say that he will go after "his woman". Superman flies back to Metropolis to save Lois, only to realize that Conduit meant Lana as "his woman".

In Lana's house, the champagne bottle suddenly explodes, but the couple are effectively saved by Superman.

Jimmy awakens inside Conduit's hold and they have some hot talks, with Conduit telling that he will be only too happy to show Jimmy, who Clark Kent really is. Superman locates Conduit's warehouse and bursts in. A brief battle ensues. Conduit is almost on the verge of defeat, when he shows Superman what he intends to do with his parents. Superman flies back to his Kansas home just in time to retrieve his parents, and flees.

At the end Superman remarks, "for all intents and purposes, Clark Kent and the whole Kent family is dead from this day on".

Notes:

  • Newstand cover by Dan Jurgens and Brett Breeding.
  • Direct sales cover by Dan Jurgens and Joe Rubinstein.
  • Direct sales cover is a partial leaf foil.
  • 48 page issue.
  • Triangle 1995 #18.
  • Chronological continuation from Superman: The Man of Steel #44.
  • Chronological continuation in Adventures of Superman #523.
